om straddle the boundaries of academia and activism. Each essay provides an account of the contributor’s personal encounters with the text, opens up the key mobilising ideas and considers how the text has the potential invigorate the political imagination of contemporary oppositional politics. This book will be of interest to students in the social sciences, especially sociology and Irish studies and will appeal to those interested or involved in political activism of any variety.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLiterature and societyzIrelandxHistory. 0aRadicalism in literature. 0aRadicalismzIrelandxHistory. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / European.2bisacsh  aIreland.  aIrish social movement.  aIvan Illich.  aOur Common Future.  aThe Myth of Mental Illness.  aThe Rights of Man.  aThomas Paine.  aThomas Szasz.  aTools for Conviviality.  aWilliam Thompson.  amedicalisation.  amobilising classics.  apolitical action.  apolitical imaginations.  apractical education.  aradical ideas.  asocialist feminism.  asustainable development.1 aDukelow, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDukelow, Fiona, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaravan, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLane, Fintan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAliskey, Bernadette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonnell, Orla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcVeigh, Robbie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeade, Rosie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Donovan, Orla, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary